5. Business Partner Collaboration
This one simulates a chat with a PM or analyst. You will get a vague ask like: “We want to track engagement.”

If you jump into events right away, you are sunk. The trick is to slow down and ask:

Engagement of what — orders, sessions, retention?
What granularity — daily, weekly, cohorts?
Which KPI actually matters — DAU, churn, repeat orders?
We practiced turning fuzzy goals into clear dashboards, and explaining technical choices in plain English. Sometimes even sketching a quick diagram helps a ton.

Lesson: This is where soft skills count. You’re being judged on whether you can make the business feel confident in your solutions.





🧩 3. Mapping Your Questions → DoorDash Evaluation Buckets
🔹 A. Metrics & KPI Definition (Most common)

“We want to track engagement / retention / satisfaction. How would you approach it?”

What DoorDash expects you to do:

Clarify the business goal

Define a north-star metric

Add supporting + diagnostic metrics

Identify data sources

Explain dashboard structure

Example structure (say this explicitly):

North-star: MAU / Orders per user / Retention

Supporting: Session frequency, conversion, churn

Diagnostics: Latency, delivery time, cancellation, cold food

Sources: Events, orders table, Dasher logs, experiments

Dashboard: Exec → Ops → Deep-dive layers

✅ This exact thinking appears in:

Engagement tracking

Dashboard design

Marketplace health

🔹 B. Business Expansion / Strategy

“DoorDash is expanding into a new area / vertical / market. How would you approach it?”

DoorDash wants to hear marketplace-first thinking:

Your answer must include:

Demand-side signals (users, frequency, AOV)

Supply-side readiness (Dashers, merchants)

Unit economics (CAC, margin, incentives)

Risk metrics (cancellations, SLA misses)

Golden line to say:

“I’d validate demand, supply, and unit economics before scaling.”

This maps to:

New vertical

International expansion

DashPass / subscriptions

Merchant tools

🔹 C. Feature / Product Success Measurement

“How would you measure success of DashPass / promo / pricing change?”

DoorDash always expects experimentation language.

You must mention:

Control vs treatment

Primary metric (incremental orders / retention)

Guardrails (margin, cancellations, Dasher earnings)

Short-term vs long-term impact

❌ Wrong: “Orders increased”
✅ Right: “Incremental lift vs counterfactual”

This covers:

Promos

Subscriptions

Recommendations

Pricing changes

🔹 D. Ambiguous Stakeholder Ask (Very DoorDash)

“Build a model/dashboard for X. Walk me through your questions.”

This is pure Business Partner signal.

They want to see:

Clarifying questions first

Pushback on vague asks

Alignment on decision-making

Strong opening line:

“Before building anything, I’d clarify what decision this enables.”

Then:

Who is the user?

What decision changes?

Accuracy vs latency?

Interpretability vs automation?

🔁 4. Drop in Sales / Orders Question (Always Asked)

“If orders drop, how would you debug?”

DoorDash expects a top-down funnel decomposition:

Is it real or data issue?

Demand-side vs supply-side?

Geography / cohort isolation

Recent changes (feature, pricing, ops)

External factors (seasonality, weather)

This question is almost guaranteed.

